1. Smoking a cigarette delivers nicotine much more slowly and at lower concentrations than injecting pure nicotine directly into a vein.
2. Smoking introduces many other chemicals and toxins besides nicotine, while injection involves only pure nicotine.
3. The physiological effects and risks of injecting pure nicotine are much more severe and immediate compared to smoking a cigarette.
4. The method of administration (inhalation vs. intravenous injection) leads to significant differences in how the body processes nicotine.
5. Smoking a cigarette involves a ritual and sensory experience that injecting pure nicotine does not replicate.